comments:
This course examines the history and significance of social contract doctrine for modern social and political thought, in particular the works of Thomas Hobbes, John Locke, and J.J. Rousseau. It also studies the utilitarian critique of social contract doctrine and the utilitarian views of David Hume, Adam Smith, J.S. Mill, and Karl Marx's criticism of liberal- democratic justice. 
This course thus serves as an introduction to many of the major figures in modern political philosophy. &#8232;&#8232;Students described this course as a “great introduction to philosophy.” Some students felt that the course gave them a “new appreciation on the subject.”&#8232;
&#8232;Students praised Professor Platz and described him as “a joy to have in class.” Students expressed that he “maintains an excellent balance between lecture and seminar.” They claim his interest in the subject is “contagious.” &#8232;&#8232;This course fulfills the Society sector requirement.
